widgets_values: Using the normals for the controlNet instead

This is a NULL regional prompt. If we don't apply some prompt to all pixels in an image, bad artifacting results. The combination of all masks, inverted is used for this. Note the invert node to the right of here.
Try other finetuned base models that specialize in photographic results. The SDXL model here is a good starting point, but certainly _much_ better results can be achieved with SDXL variants.

Base SDXL is very sensitive to the controlnet conditioning on the floor. The use of the mask, and the start percent can have a dramatic effect.

This performs much better using photographic finetuned models.

nodes.title: prompt_negative
widgets_values: cartoon, illustration,(blur, blurry, grainy), cropped, out of frame, cut off, out of focus, glitch, duplicate, deformed, (amateur:1.3), merging, clipping, person, human, text, logo

This outline image is used for one of the controlnets. It strongly guides the structure of the generation. Mostly it keeps the generations from going outside the bounds or adding new things to the image.
This mask guides the per pixel weight of the controlnet. With this you can strongly apply the controlnet to some parts of the image, and not at all to other parts.

These nodes control the prompts for the regions. Change these for image variations.

Note the global prompt is also included. You could use a string concat, but this was left out to avoid a lot of 3rd party node dependencies.
These images are saved to the 'ComfyUI_windows_portable\ComfyUI\output' folder.

This slightly blurred masked image is used for the inpainting with differential diffusion. It informs the model how much of the original image should be retained. This is useful for when you only want to slightly alter a portion of the image, say add a little bit of dirt to the forklift (denoise value of 0.2), versus a full denoise to completely reimage the forklift and strongly follow the forklift prompt.

NOTE: Unless you use a full denoise of 1.0 for the forklift, it won't consistently change to the color in the prompt (if you specified one)

The image is recomposited with a mask with the original image. Despite a denoise value of zero, the model still tweaks the pixels from areas that are not intended to be edited. Mostly, this is noticeable in text. So we do this.
